===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|attenden|lang=enm}}, {{term|atenden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|atendre||to attend, listen|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|attendere||to stretch toward, give heed to|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad||to}} + {{term|tendere||to stretch}}; see [[tend]] and compare [[attempt]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|archaic|transitive|lang=en}} To [[listen]] to (something or someone); to pay attention to; regard; heed. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* Sir {{w|Philip Sidney}} (1554-1586)
#*: The diligent pilot in a dangerous tempest doth not '''attend''' the unskilful words of the passenger.
# {{context|archaic|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[listen]] ({{term|to}}, {{term|unto}}). {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
# {{senseid|en|to turn one's consideration to, deal with}}{{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To turn one's [[consideration]] ({{term|to}}); to [[deal]] with (a task, problem, concern etc.), to look after. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|Secretaries '''attend''' to correspondence.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=15
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=Edward Churchill still '''attended''' to his work in a hopeless mechanical manner like a sleep-walker who walks safely on a well-known round. But his Roman collar galled him, his cossack stifled him, his biretta was as uncomfortable as a merry-andrew's cap and bells.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[wait upon]] as a [[servant]] etc.; to accompany to assist (someone). {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|Valets '''attend''' to their employer's wardrobe.}}
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: The fifth had charge sick persons to '''attend'''.
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}} (1564-1616)
#*: '''Attends''' the emperor in his royal court.
#* {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Thomas Macaulay}} (1800-1859)
#*: With a sore heart and a gloomy brow, he prepared to '''attend''' William thither.
# {{senseid|en|to be present at}}{{context|transitive|lang=en}} To be [[present]] at (an event or place) in order to take part in some action or proceedings. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|Children must '''attend''' primary school.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=5
|passage=In the eyes of Mr. Farquhar Fenelon Cooke the apotheosis of the Celebrity was complete. The people of Asquith were not only willing to '''attend''' the house-warming, but had been worked up to the pitch of eagerness. The Celebrity as a matter of course was master of ceremonies.}}
#* '''1994''', {{w|Nelson Mandela}}, ''{{w|Long Walk to Freedom}}'', Abacus 2010, p. 20:
#*: I '''attended''' a one-room school next door to the palace and studied English, Xhosa, history and geography.
# To be present with; to accompany; to be united or consequent to.
#: {{usex|lang=en|a measure '''attended''' with ill effects}}
#* {{w|John Dryden}} (1631-1700)
#*: What cares must then '''attend''' the toiling swain.
#* {{quote-book|year=1922|author={{w|Ben Travers}}
|chapter=5|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1521052W A Cuckoo in the Nest]
|passage=The most rapid and most seductive transition in all human nature is that which '''attends''' the palliation of a ravenous appetite.  There is something humiliating about it.{{...}}Can those harmless but refined fellow-diners be the selfish cads whose gluttony and personal appearance so raised your contemptuous wrath on your arrival?}}
# To wait for; to await; to remain, abide, or be in store for.
#* {{w|John Locke}} (1632-1705)
#*: the state that '''attends''' all men after this
#* {{w|John Dryden}} (1631-1700)
#*: Three days I promised to '''attend''' my doom.

